<subsection xml:id="subsection-1-3-1">
    <title>Definition of a Limit</title>
    <p>
        Let's consider the function <md>\frac{x^2+x-2}{x-1}.</md>  
        Graphically, this is a line with a hole at the point <m>(1,3)</m>, as seen below.  
        That is, <m>f(1)</m> does not exist.  
        However, the limit as <m>x</m> approaches <m>1</m> does.  
        We see that as <m>x</m> values tend toward <m>1</m>, the function values tend toward <m>3</m>.  
        In fact, the function gets as arbitrarily-close to <m>3</m> as we would ever like.  
        In symbols, we would write <md>\lim_{x\rightarrow 1} \frac{x^2 + x -2}{x-1} = 3.</md>
    </p>

     <figure xml:id="limit-exam">
        <caption><m>\frac{x^2+x-2}{x-1}</m> with hole at 1 displayed.</caption>
        <image width="80%" xml:id="limit-exam-1">
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw [&lt;->,thick](-3,0)--(5,0);
                    \draw[&lt;->,thick] (0,-2)--(0,6);
                    \draw[->,thick,blue] (1.1,3.1)--(3.9,5.9);
                    \draw[->,thick,blue] (0.9,2.9)--(-2.9,-0.9);
                    \draw (1,-.1)--(1,.1);
                    \draw (-.1,3)--(.1,3);
                    \draw (1,-.3) node{$1$};
                    \draw (-.3,3) node{$3$};
                    \draw (1,3) circle (4pt);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
         We give the formal definition of <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) = L</m> below.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-limit-at-a">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>f(x)</m> be a real-valued function and let <m>a</m> be a real number.  
                We say <md>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) = L</md> if for every <m>\epsilon > 0</m> there is some <m>\delta>0</m> so that for each <m>x</m>, 
                <m>a-\delta &lt; x &lt; a+\delta</m> and <m>x\ne a</m> implies that <m>L-\epsilon &lt; f(x) &lt; L + \epsilon</m>.<idx>limit</idx>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        The definition of a limit can be hard to parse.  Consider the more intuitive version below.
    </p>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) = L</m> means that no matter how close we want the function <m>f(x)</m> to be to the value <m>L</m> (within <m>\epsilon</m>), 
            we can find a sufficiently small range of <m>x</m> values close to <m>a</m>> (within <m>\delta</m>) that guarantees <m>f(x)</m> is desirably close to <m>L</m>.  
        </p>
    </insight>

    <p>
        An important note in a calculus course is that the interpretation of "<m>x</m> closer to <m>a</m> implies <m>f(x)</m> closer to <m>L</m>"" is not quite right and has some counter examples.  
        This is why the definition of the limit is a bit more technical than many believe it should be.
    </p>

    <p>
        In the following table, we provide a list of common limit rules/shortcuts.  This are quite intuitive and shouldn't be expressly memorized.
    </p>

    <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-common-limits">
        <title>Common Limits</title>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>\lim_{x\to a} f(x)=L</m> and <m>\lim_{x\to a} g(x)=M</m>. Then:
        </p>

        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>For any constant <m>c</m>, <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} c = c</m>.</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>For any constant <m>c</m>, <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} c\cdot f(x) = c\cdot \lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) = c\cdot L</m>.</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} x = a</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) \pm g(x) = \lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) \pm \lim_{x\rightarrow a} g(x) = L \pm M</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) \cdot g(x) = \left(\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x)\right) \cdot \left(\lim_{x\rightarrow a} g(x)\right) = L\cdot M</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Suppose <m>M\ne 0</m>.  Then <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \frac{\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x)}{\lim_{x\rightarrow a} g(x)} = \frac{L}{M}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Suppose <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow L} h(x) = N.</m>  Then <m>{\lim_{x\rightarrow a} h(f(x)) = \lim_{x\rightarrow L} h(x) = N}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </assemblage>

    <example xml:id="ex-limits">
        <title>Limits</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate the following limits.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow 3} e^{-2x+1} - 5
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow \pi/2} \sin(\cos(3x))
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow -3} \sqrt[4]{5x+30}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>e^{-5}-5</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt[4]{15}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \begin{aligned}
                                    \lim_{x\rightarrow 3} e^{-2x+1} - 5 &amp;= \lim_{x\rightarrow 3} e^{-2x+1} - \lim_{x\rightarrow 3} 5\\
                                    &amp;= e^{\lim_{x\rightarrow 3} -2x + 1} - 5\\
                                    &amp; = e^{-2 \left(\lim_{x\rightarrow 3} x\right) + \left(\lim_{x\rightarrow 3} 1\right)} - 5\\
                                    &amp; = e^{-2\cdot 3 + 1} - 5\\
                                    &amp; = e^{-5} - 5.
                                \end{aligned}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \begin{aligned}
                                    \lim_{x\rightarrow \pi/2} \sin(\cos(3x)) &amp;= \sin \left( \cos\left( \lim_{x\rightarrow \pi/2} 3x\right)\right)\\
                                    &amp;= \sin \left( \cos\left( \frac{3\pi}{2}\right)\right)\\
                                    &amp;=\sin(0) = 0
                                \end{aligned}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \begin{aligned}
                                    \lim_{x\rightarrow -3} \sqrt[4]{5x+30} &amp;= \sqrt[4]{\lim_{x\rightarrow -3} (5x+30)}\\
                                    &amp;= \sqrt[4]{5 \lim_{x\rightarrow -3} x + \lim_{x\rightarrow -3} 30}\\
                                    &amp;= \sqrt[4]{5\cdot (-3) + 30}\\
                                    &amp;= \sqrt[4]{15}
                                \end{aligned}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
        Note that all of these functions are continuous around the desired <m>a</m> values, so we could just simply plug in the <m>a</m> values into the functions to get the desired limits.
        While there are certainly more complex and interesting limit examples, the P exam is not a calculus exam; limits are relatively straightforward.
    </p>

    <p>
        Sometimes limits do not approach a finite value but instead tend to <m>\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m>.  
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-unbounded-limits">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We say <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) = \infty</m> if for every <m>L</m> there is some <m>\delta</m> so that for each <m>x</m> with <m>0&lt;|x-a|&lt;\delta</m> we have <m>f(x) > L</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We say <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow a} f(x) = -\infty</m> if for every <m>L</m> there is some <m>\delta</m> so that for each <m>x</m> with <m>0&lt;|x-a|&lt;\delta</m> we have <m>f(x) &lt; L</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        These definitions essentially mean that for <m>x</m> values sufficiently close to <m>a</m> we have the function tending toward <m>\pm \infty</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="limits-ti-infinity">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{x^2} = \infty
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow \pi/2} -(\tan(x))^2 = \lim_{x\rightarrow \pi/2} -\left(\frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}\right)^2 = -\infty
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>
</subsection>